(The Story of Hrafnkell, Frey’s Priest)Tj
/TT4 1 Tf
11 0 0 11 71 710 Tm
(1882 translation into English by John Coles from the original Icelandic ’Hrafnkels saga freysgoða’.)Tj
/TT2 1 Tf
17 0 0 17 71 676 Tm
(Chapter 1)Tj
/TT4 1 Tf
11 0 0 11 71 651.8 Tm
(It was in the days of King Harold Fairhair that a man brought his ship to Iceland into Breiðdal, his)Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(name being Hallfreðr. Breiðdal is a countryside down below that of Fljótsdalr. On board his ship was)Tj
T*
(his wife and son, who was hight Hrafnkell, who was then fifteen winters old, a hopeful man and a)Tj
T*
(goodly. Hallfreðr set up household. In the course of the winter there died a servant-maid of foreign)Tj
T*
(kin, whose name was Arnthrúðr; hence the name of the place Arnthruðr-staðir. In the spring Hallfreðr)Tj
T*
(moved his house northward over the heath, and set up a home at a place called Geitdalr. One night he)Tj
T*
(dreamt that there came a man to him, and said : "There liest thou, Hallfreðr, and rather unwarily; flit)Tj
T*
(thy house away west across the Lagarfljót, for there all thy good luck awaits thee." Thereupon he)Tj
T*
(awoke and flitted his belongings down valley across Rangá, into the Tongue, to a spot, which has since)Tj
T*
(been called Hallfreðr-staðir, and there he dwelt into a good old age. In breaking up from Geitdalr he)Tj
T*
(had left a goat and a buck behind, and the same day that Hallfreðr left, an earthslip struck the house,)Tj
T*
(and there these two creatures were lost. Hence the name Geitdalr, which this place has borne ever )Tj
T*
(since.)Tj
/TT2 1 Tf
17 0 0 17 71 459.4001 Tm
(Chapter 2)Tj
/TT4 1 Tf
11 0 0 11 71 435.2001 Tm
(Hrafnkell made it his wont to ride upon the heaths in the summer-seasons. At this time Jökuldalr was)Tj
T*
(all settled as high as the bridge. Once Hrafnkell rode up along Fljótsdalhérað and saw that a certain)Tj
T*
(void valley stretched up beyond Jökuldalr, which seemed to him to be a better settlement than other)Tj
T*
(valleys which he had seen already. And when he came home, he asked his father to share him out his)Tj
T*
(part in the property, saying, that he was minded to set up house in the valley. This his father granted)Tj
T*
(him, and in the valley he had found, he made an abode for himself, which he called Aðalból. Hrafnkell)Tj
T*
(got him for wife Oddbjörg, daughter of Skjaldúlfr, from Laxárdalr, with whom he begat two sons, the)Tj
T*
(older hight Thórir, the younger Ásbjörn. But when Hrafnkell had hallowed for himself the land of)Tj
T*
(Aðalból, he held a great sacrificial feast, and a great temple, too, he reared up there. Hrafnkell loved)Tj
T*
(no other god before Frey, and to him he made offerings of all the best things he had, going half-shares.)Tj
T*
(Hrafnkell settled the whole of the valley, bestowing lands on other people, on condition of being their)Tj
T*
(chief; and thus he assumed priesthood over them. From this it came to pass that his name was)Tj
T*
(lengthened, and he was called Freysgoði. He was a man of right unruly ways, but a well-mannered)Tj
T*
(man notwithstanding. He asserted the authority of a priest over all the men of Jokuldalr. Hrafnkell was)Tj
T*
(meek and blithe towards his own people, but stern and crossgrained towards those of Jokuldalr, who)Tj
T*
(never got fair dealings with him. He busied himself much with single combats, and for no man did he)Tj
T*
(pay a weregild, and one ever brought him to do boot for whatsoever he might have done.)Tj
0 -2.2 TD
(The country side of Fljótsdalr is a right difficult one to traverse, stony and sloughy. Yet father and son)Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(would be constantly riding to see each other, for between them there was much fondness of love.)Tj
T*
(Hallfreðr thought the common way was too difficult of passing, so he sought for a new road above the)Tj
T*
(fells, which stand in the country-sides of Fljótsdalr, where he found a drier one, although a longer,)Tj
T*
(which ever since has been called the "gate" of Hallfreðr. This road is traversed only by those who are)Tj
T*
(well acquainted with the country-sides.)Tj
