(There was a man named Bjarni, who dwelt at a stead called Langarhús, in Hrafnkelsdalr. He was)Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(married, and had begotten sons with his wife, one of whom was called Sámr, the other Eyvindr,)Tj
T*
(goodly men and promising; Eyvindr stayed at home with his father, but Sámr was married, and had his)Tj
T*
(abode on the northern side of the valley at a place called Leikskálar, and was right well off for)Tj
T*
(live-stock. Sámr was a turbulent fellow, and skilled in law withal; but Eyvindr became a traveller, and)Tj
T*
(went to Norway, where he dwelt for the first winter; from there he went abroad into foreign lands,)Tj
T*
(coming at last to a stay in Constantinople, where he was right honourably received by the Greek king,)Tj
T*
(and where, for a while, he spent his time.)Tj
0 -2.2 TD
(Of all his possessions there was one for which Hrafnkell had greater fondness than any other. This was)Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(a horse of a roan colour, which he called "Freymane." He gave unto his friend Frey the half of this)Tj
T*
(horse, and so great a love had he for it, that he made a solemn vow that he would kill any one who)Tj
T*
(should ride the horse without his leave.)Tj
/TT2 1 Tf
17 0 0 17 71 522.2001 Tm
(Chapter 4)Tj
/TT4 1 Tf
11 0 0 11 71 498.0002 Tm
(A man was hight Thorbjörn, brother of Bjarni, who dwelt at a stead in Hrafnkelsdalr, called Hóll,)Tj
T*
(situated across the valley right against Aðalból, on the eastern side. Thorbjörn was a man of scanty)Tj
T*
(means, but of many useless mouths. The eldest of his sons was called Einarr; he was a tall man and)Tj
T*
(well-mannered withal. It so happened one spring that Thorbjörn said to Einarr that he had better try to)Tj
T*
(secure some place for himself; "for," said he, "I am in want of no more work than can be done by the)Tj
T*
(hands that are here already, but thou wilt find it easy to secure a situation, able and skilful as thou art.)Tj
T*
(It is not for any want of love that I thus call upon thee to go away, for thou art to me the most useful of)Tj
T*
(all my children; but it is because of my small means and poverty; but my other children must grow up)Tj
T*
(labourers, but as for thee, thou wilt find it easier to get a place than they." Einarr answered : "Too late)Tj
T*
(hast thou let me know of this, as now all places and situations, the best of them at least, are already)Tj
T*
(arranged for, and I deem it an undesirable thing to have to accept only the worst." Now Einarr took his)Tj
T*
(horse and rode to Aðalból, where Hrafnkell sat in his chamber, and received him well and joyfully.)Tj
T*
(Einarr applied for a situation with Hrafnkell, and he answered : "Why askest so late for this? otherwise)Tj
T*
(I should have taken thee the first of all men. Now I have secured all my servants, except for that one)Tj
T*
(business which, I fear, thou art not minded to undertake." Einarr asked what it was. Hrafnkell)Tj
T*
(answered, he had got no one to take charge of his sheep, but said he was in great need of one. Einarr)Tj
T*
(said he did not mind what work he did, whether this or any other; but said he would like to settle with)Tj
T*
(him for cloth and board wages. "I’ll make a short bargain with thee," said Hrafnkell. "Thy business)Tj
T*
(shall be to watch fifteen ewes at the mountain dairy, and gather and carry home faggots for summer)Tj
T*
(fuel. On these terms thou shalt take service with me for two ’half-years.’ But a one thing I must give)Tj
T*
(thee, as all my shepherds, to understand: ’Freymane’ goes grazing in the valley with his band of)Tj
T*
(mares; thou shalt take care of him winter and summer; but I warn thee of one thing, namely, that thou)Tj
T*
(never be on his back on any condition whatever, for I am bound by a mighty vow to slay the man that)Tj
T*
(ever should have a ride on him. There are twelve mares with him; whichever one of these thou mayest)Tj
T*
(want, night or day, is at your service. Do now as I tell thee, and mind the old saw: ’No blame is borne)Tj
T*
(by those who warn.’ Now thou knowest what I have said." Einarr said he trusted he was under no such)Tj
T*
(luckless spell as to ride on a horse which was forbidden, least of all when there were other horses at)Tj
T*
(his disposal.)Tj
