(Now Einarr goes home for his clothes, and betakes himself to Aðalból. Thereupon they brought the)Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(milking-stock to the mountain-dairy up in Hrafnkelsdalr, which was set up at a place called)Tj
T*
(Grjótteigssel. During the summer all went in a fair way with Einarr, so that never a ewe was missing)Tj
T*
(up to mid-summer; but then, one night, it came to pass that nearly thirty of them had strayed away.)Tj
T*
(Einarr went all over the sheep-walks, searching without finding any, and for nearly a week the sheep)Tj
T*
(were missing. One morning Einarr rose early, and, coming out, found that all the fog from the south)Tj
T*
(and the drizzle had lifted. And so he takes into his hand a staff and a bridle, and a riding-rug. Then he)Tj
T*
(went on, passing Grjótteigsá, which ran above the dairy. On the shingly flats by the river were lying)Tj
T*
(about all the sheep that had been home in the evening before. These he drove home towards the dairy,)Tj
T*
(and then went in search of those that were wanting. He now saw the stud-horses further afield on the)Tj
T*
(flats, and was minded to secure one of them to ride on, knowing that he would cover ground more)Tj
T*
(quickly by riding than by walking: and when he came to the horses, he had to run about after them,)Tj
T*
(they being now shy, though never before they used to run away from any one -- except "Freymane")Tj
T*
(alone. He was as quiet as if stuck buried in the ground. Einarr, seeing that the morning was passing)Tj
T*
(off, thought that Hrafnkell surely would never know if he rode upon the horse, and so he took it, put)Tj
T*
(on it the bridle, and the riding-rug on his back under himself, and rode up past the gorge of Grjóta, and)Tj
T*
