T*
(for it was the best of horses. Then it came into Einarr’s mind that it was time already to drive home to)Tj
T*
(the dairy the sheep which were still in safe keeping, letting alone those that he could not find. So he)Tj
T*
(rode to the eastward over the mountain-necks into Hrafnkelsdalr. But as he came down by Grjótteigr,)Tj
T*
(he heard the bleating of sheep along the river-gorge, even where he had ridden close by before; and)Tj
T*
(turning thither, sees how thirty ewes come running along towards him, even the very ones which had)Tj
T*
(been missing for a whole week already, and these, with the rest of the ewes, he drove along home to)Tj
T*
(the dairy. The horse was all foaming with sweat, so that every hair on him was dripping; bespattered)Tj
T*
(he was all over with mire, and mightily blown. Twelve times he rolled himself, and then he set up a)Tj
T*
(mighty neighing, and then set off at a swift pace down along the beaten tracks. Einarr ran forthwith)Tj
T*
(after him, endeavouring to overtake him, and to lay hand on him and bring him back to the horses. But)Tj
T*
(now "Freymane" was so shy, that Einarr could get nowhere near him. Thus the horse ran down all)Tj
T*
(along the valley, never stopping until it came home to Aðalból. At the time Hrafnkell sat at table, and)Tj
T*
(when the horse came before the door it neighed aloud. Hrafnkell told one of the handmaidens who)Tj
T*
(were serving at table, to go to the door, "for I heard the neighing of a horse, and meseemed the)Tj
T*
(neighing was like to that of ’Frey-mayne.’" She went out to the door, and there beheld "Freymane" in a)Tj
T*
(most ungainly plight. She told Hrafnkell that "Freymane" stood outside the door most ill-favoured of)Tj
T*
(look. "What is the matter with the champion that he should come home as at this time," says Hrafnkell;)Tj
T*
("sure that bodes no good." Then he went out and saw "Freymane," and spoke to him: "I am sorry to)Tj
T*
