(It is stated that there came a certain ship into Reiðarfjörðr, the master of which was Eyvindr)Tj
0 -1.2 TD
(Bjarnason, who had been abroad for seven winters together. Eyvindr had bettered himself greatly as to)Tj
T*
(manners, and had now become the briskest of men. Now he soon was told of the tidings which had)Tj
T*
(come to pass, and he made as if he took little heed thereof, being a man of unmeddlesome ways. When)Tj
T*
(Sámr heard this he rode to the ship, and a great joyful meeting there was between the brothers. Sámr)Tj
T*
(asked him to come up west to his place, and Eyvindr accepted it, and bade Sámr ride home first, and)Tj
T*
(afterwards send him horses for his chattels. He hauled his ship aland, and made her snug. Now Sámr)Tj
T*
