(Now Sámr brought all the chattels home to Aðalból; and when he came home Sámr sent for his)Tj
T*
(retainers to be there with him the next morning by the hour of day-meal \(9 o’clock A.M.\), being)Tj
T*
(minded to set off eastward over the heath, "And let our journey now take its own turn." In the evening)Tj
T*
(Sámr went to bed, and a goodly gathering of people there was there. Hrafnkell rode home and told the)Tj
T*
(tidings that had befallen. Having partaken of a repast, he gathers to him men, even to the number of)Tj
T*
(seventy, with which gathering he rides west over the heath, and coming unawares upon Aðalból, he)Tj
T*
(took Sámr in his bed, and had him brought out. Then Hrafnkell spoke : "Now thy conditions have)Tj
T*
(come to such a pass, Sámr, as surely a short while ago thou wouldst not have believed, I having now in)Tj
T*
(my hand the power of thy life. Yet I shall not deal with thee in more unmanly manner than thou didst)Tj
T*
(to me. Now two conditions I put before thee -- one, to be slain; the other, that I settle and arrange all)Tj
T*
(things between me and thee." Sámr said that he would rather choose to live, though he well knew that)Tj
T*
(that condition would be hard enough. To that Hrafnkell bade him be sure to make up his mind, "For)Tj
T*
(that is a requital I owe thee; and I should deal with thee better by half, if thou art worthy of it. Thou)Tj
T*
(shalt be off from Aðalból, and betake thee to Leikskálar, and there set up thy house; thou shalt take)Tj
T*
(with thee all the wealth that belonged to Eyvindr, but from hence thou shalt take with thee of money’s)Tj
T*
(worth, so much as thou didst bring hither; that only shalt thou bring away. I shall overtake again my)Tj
T*
(priesthood, and my house, and my property; and great as I see the increase of my wealth has grown,)Tj
T*
(thou shalt enjoy nought thereof notwithstanding; for Eyvindr, thy brother, no weregild shall be)Tj
T*
(forthcoming, even for this reason, that thou didst plead so provokingly after thy kinsman: for thou)Tj
T*
(hast, indeed, had plentiful weregild for Einarr, thy relation, in having enjoyed my rule and my wealth)Tj
T*
(for six years together; but the slaying of Eyvindr and his men, I value no more than the mutilation)Tj
T*
(wrought on me and my men. Thou didst drive me out of my country-side; but I am content that thou)Tj
T*
(abide at Leikskálar; and that will do for thee, if thou rush not into over-boldness, that may bring about)Tj
T*
(thy shame. My underling thou shalt remain while we are both alive. Be thou sure of this, too, that)Tj
T*
